---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Design System Health Audit (Sample): Component Debt"
  description="A sample Design System Health Audit deliverable: executive summary, severity-graded findings, and a prioritized remediation roadmap. Findings and client are illustrative."
>
  <section class="hero cover">
    <div class="page">
      <p class="kicker">Design System Health Audit</p>
      <h1>Northwind Health: Web Platform UI</h1>
      <p class="sub">
        Findings, severity, and a prioritized remediation roadmap.
      </p>
      <div class="meta">
        <div><b>Prepared for</b>Northwind Health, Inc. (sample)</div>
        <div><b>Prepared by</b>Andrew Reysen, Frontend and Design Systems</div>
        <div>
          <b>Scope</b>Web app: component library, tokens, theming, accessibility
        </div>
        <div><b>Date</b>Sample report</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="page">
    <section class="card">
      <h2>Executive summary</h2>
      <p class="lead">
        Northwind's web UI works, but it has grown without a shared system. The
        same elements are built several different ways across the app, color and
        spacing values are hard-coded rather than tokenized, and several
        components fall short of accessibility standards. The result is slower
        feature work, visible inconsistency for users, and avoidable
        accessibility risk.
      </p>
      <p>
        This audit reviewed the component library, styling approach, theming,
        and accessibility across the primary web application. It identifies
        <strong>3 high, 4 medium, and 3 low</strong> severity issues, and lays out
        a prioritized roadmap to move from an ad hoc UI to a maintainable design system.
        None of the issues are catastrophic; together they are a steady tax on velocity
        and quality that compounds as the team grows.
      </p>

      <div class="scores">
        <div class="score">
          <div class="n grade">C&minus;</div><div class="l">Overall health</div>
        </div>
        <div class="score">
          <div class="n">10</div><div class="l">Findings</div>
        </div>
        <div class="score">
          <div class="n">6</div><div class="l">Button variants found</div>
        </div>
        <div class="score">
          <div class="n">0</div><div class="l">Shared token files</div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="note score-note">
        Grade reflects consistency, reuse, theming readiness, and accessibility
        against common design-system maturity benchmarks. "6 button variants"
        means six visually different button implementations doing the same job.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>What was reviewed</h2>
      <ul class="clean">
        <li>
          Component library and shared UI code (structure, duplication, naming)
        </li>
        <li>
          Styling approach: hard-coded values versus design tokens; CSS
          organization
        </li>
        <li>Theming and white-label readiness</li>
        <li>
          Accessibility: color contrast, focus states, semantic markup, keyboard
          support
        </li>
        <li>Design-to-code consistency (Figma intent versus shipped UI)</li>
      </ul>
      <h2 class="legend-heading">Severity legend</h2>
      <div class="legend">
        <span
          ><span class="sev crit">High</span> Costs velocity or creates user or accessibility
          risk now.</span
        >
        <span
          ><span class="sev med">Medium</span> Meaningful drag; fix soon.</span
        >
        <span
          ><span class="sev low">Low</span> Polish; fix opportunistically.</span
        >
      </div>
      <p class="note">
        Severity is shown by shape and label as well as color, so it reads
        clearly for everyone including colorblind readers.
      </p>
    </section>

    <h2 class="findings-heading">Findings</h2>

    <div class="finding crit">
      <div class="head">
        <span class="id">DS-01</span><span class="sev crit">High</span>
      </div>
      <h3>No design tokens; color and spacing are hard-coded everywhere</h3>
      <div class="where">Found across 40+ component and stylesheet files</div>
      <p>
        Brand colors, spacing, and font sizes are written as literal values (for
        example <code>#2f6fed</code>, <code>16px</code>) scattered through the
        codebase rather than referenced from a central token source. The same
        blue appears as <code>#2f6fed</code>, <code>#2e6fed</code>, and
        <code>#3170ee</code> in different places, which is three "brand blues" that
        are meant to be one.
      </p>
      <div class="label">Example</div>
      <pre
        class="code"><span class="c">/* card.css */</span>
.card-title &#123; color: #2f6fed; padding: 16px; &#125;
<span class="c">/* banner.css, same intent, different values */</span>
.banner h2  &#123; color: #3170ee; padding: 15px; &#125;</pre>
      <div class="label">Recommendation</div>
      <p>
        Introduce a three-layer token system: primitive (raw values), semantic (<code
          >--color-brand</code
        >, <code>--space-md</code>), and component. Migrate hard-coded values to
        semantic tokens. This is the highest-impact change in this report;
        nearly every other issue gets easier once tokens exist.
      </p>
      <div class="impact">
        <strong>Impact:</strong> Brand changes become a one-line edit instead of a
        find-and-replace across the codebase. Theming and white-labeling become possible
        (see DS-04).
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="finding crit">
      <div class="head">
        <span class="id">DS-02</span><span class="sev crit">High</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Six different button implementations</h3>
      <div class="where">
        btn.css, Button.tsx, LegacyButton.tsx, inline styles in 3 views
      </div>
      <p>
        The app has at least six visually distinct ways to render a button, with
        different padding, radius, hover behavior, and disabled states. New work
        copies whichever one is nearest, so the count keeps growing. Users see
        subtly different buttons across screens.
      </p>
      <div class="label">Recommendation</div>
      <p>
        Build one canonical <code>Button</code> component with documented variants
        (primary, secondary, ghost, destructive) and sizes. Replace the others incrementally,
        starting with the highest-traffic screens. Add a lint rule that flags raw
        <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> styling outside the component.
      </p>
      <div class="impact">
        <strong>Impact:</strong> One place to fix bugs and accessibility; consistent
        UX; faster feature work because engineers stop re-deciding button styling.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="finding crit">
      <div class="head">
        <span class="id">A11Y-01</span><span class="sev crit">High</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Primary button fails WCAG AA color contrast</h3>
      <div class="where">
        Primary button: white text <code>#ffffff</code> on <code>#5b9bd5</code>
      </div>
      <p>
        The primary action button has a text-to-background contrast ratio of
        about
        <strong>2.6:1</strong>. WCAG AA requires <strong>4.5:1</strong> for normal
        text. This is the most-clicked element in the product and it is hard to read
        for low-vision users, and a measurable accessibility-compliance gap.
      </p>
      <div class="label">Recommendation</div>
      <p>
        Darken the button background to approximately <code>#2c6ca6</code> (about
        4.6:1 with white) or darken the text. Once tokens exist (DS-01), enforce contrast
        at the token level so it cannot regress.
      </p>
      <div class="impact">
        <strong>Impact:</strong> Removes compliance risk, improves usability for all
        users, and is a quick win.
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="finding med">
      <div class="head">
        <span class="id">DS-03</span><span class="sev med">Medium</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Inconsistent spacing scale</h3>
      <div class="where">
        Global; spacing values range freely from 4px to 40px
      </div>
      <p>
        Spacing uses arbitrary values (13px, 15px, 18px, 22px) rather than a
        fixed scale. Layouts look slightly "off" in places and engineers guess
        at values.
      </p>
      <div class="label">Recommendation</div>
      <p>
        Adopt a spacing scale (4, 8, 12, 16, 24, 32, 48) as semantic tokens and
        snap existing values to the nearest step.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="finding med">
      <div class="head">
        <span class="id">DS-04</span><span class="sev med">Medium</span>
      </div>
      <h3>No theming layer; white-label is not feasible today</h3>
      <div class="where">Styling architecture</div>
      <p>
        Because values are hard-coded (DS-01), the app cannot be re-themed for a
        partner or a dark mode without editing source throughout. If multi-brand
        or dark mode is on the roadmap, this is a blocker.
      </p>
      <div class="label">Recommendation</div>
      <p>
        Once semantic tokens land, add a theme layer that overrides token values
        per brand or mode. This is incremental on top of DS-01, not separate
        work.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="finding med">
      <div class="head">
        <span class="id">A11Y-02</span><span class="sev med">Medium</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Missing visible focus states on interactive elements</h3>
      <div class="where">Custom dropdowns, icon buttons, card links</div>
      <p>
        Several interactive elements remove the browser's default focus outline
        without replacing it. Keyboard users cannot tell where they are on the
        page, which fails WCAG 2.4.7.
      </p>
      <div class="label">Recommendation</div>
      <p>
        Add a consistent, token-driven <code>:focus-visible</code> style to the shared
        components. One fix in the canonical components covers most of the app.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="finding med">
      <div class="head">
        <span class="id">DS-05</span><span class="sev med">Medium</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Component naming and folder structure are inconsistent</h3>
      <div class="where">src/components, src/ui, src/shared (overlapping)</div>
      <p>
        Shared components live in three different folders with mixed naming
        conventions (<code>PascalCase</code>, <code>kebab-case</code>,
        abbreviations). New engineers cannot predict where a component lives or
        what to call a new one.
      </p>
      <div class="label">Recommendation</div>
      <p>
        Consolidate to a single <code>ui/</code> library with a documented naming
        convention and an index. Document it in the contributing guide.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="finding low">
      <div class="head">
        <span class="id">DS-06</span><span class="sev low">Low</span>
      </div>
      <h3>No component documentation or living examples</h3>
      <div class="where">No Storybook or equivalent</div>
      <p>
        There is no place to see components in isolation, so engineers read
        source to learn usage and designers cannot verify what shipped.
      </p>
      <div class="label">Recommendation</div>
      <p>
        Stand up Storybook for the canonical components as they are built. Pairs
        naturally with the DS-02 button work.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="finding low">
      <div class="head">
        <span class="id">DS-07</span><span class="sev low">Low</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Icon usage is mixed (inline SVG, icon font, and PNGs)</h3>
      <div class="where">Header, nav, empty states</div>
      <p>
        Three icon delivery methods coexist, increasing bundle size and visual
        inconsistency in stroke weight and sizing.
      </p>
      <div class="label">Recommendation</div>
      <p>
        Standardize on a single inline-SVG icon set wrapped in one
        <code>Icon</code> component with size tokens.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="finding low">
      <div class="head">
        <span class="id">A11Y-03</span><span class="sev low">Low</span>
      </div>
      <h3>Some images and icon buttons lack accessible labels</h3>
      <div class="where">Dashboard icon buttons; a few content images</div>
      <p>
        Icon-only buttons and a handful of images are missing
        <code>aria-label</code> or <code>alt</code> text, so screen readers announce
        them as unlabeled.
      </p>
      <div class="label">Recommendation</div>
      <p>
        Add labels; bake the requirement into the <code>Icon</code> and
        <code>Button</code> components so it is hard to omit.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Prioritized remediation roadmap</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        Ordered by impact. The first phase unblocks most of the rest.
      </p>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Phase</th><th>Work</th><th>Addresses</th><th>Effort</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><b>1. Foundation</b></td>
            <td
              >Introduce 3-layer design tokens; migrate the highest-traffic
              screens</td
            >
            <td>DS-01, DS-03, A11Y-01</td>
            <td class="eff">about 1 to 2 weeks</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><b>2. Core components</b></td>
            <td
              >Build canonical Button and Icon; add focus states; start
              Storybook</td
            >
            <td>DS-02, DS-06, DS-07, A11Y-02, A11Y-03</td>
            <td class="eff">about 2 weeks</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><b>3. Theming</b></td>
            <td>Add theme override layer (dark mode and white-label ready)</td>
            <td>DS-04</td>
            <td class="eff">about 1 week</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><b>4. Structure and guardrails</b></td>
            <td
              >Consolidate component folders; add lint rules to prevent
              regression</td
            >
            <td>DS-05, ongoing</td>
            <td class="eff">about 1 week</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p class="note">
        Effort assumes one focused engineer and is incremental; the app keeps
        shipping throughout. I can scope and deliver phases 1 and 2 as a
        follow-on engagement.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>What is already working</h2>
      <ul class="clean">
        <li>
          Component logic is generally clean and well-separated from styling,
          which gives tokenization a clean place to start.
        </li>
        <li>
          The team already uses a single CSS approach (no competing frameworks),
          so there is one place to introduce tokens.
        </li>
        <li>
          Recent components show better patterns than older ones, so the team's
          instincts are right; they just lack a shared system to apply them.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p class="muted">
        This is a healthy starting point. The issues here are typical of a
        product that grew faster than its UI foundation, and they are very
        fixable.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h2>Recommended next steps</h2>
      <ul class="clean">
        <li>
          <strong>Quick wins this week:</strong> fix the primary-button contrast (A11Y-01)
          and add focus states (A11Y-02). Low effort, immediate user and compliance
          benefit.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Highest impact:</strong> begin Phase 1 (tokens). Everything else
          gets easier afterward.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Optional:</strong> I can deliver Phases 1 and 2 as a fixed-scope
          remediation engagement, leaving your team with a documented system and the
          guardrails to keep it healthy.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <div class="report-foot">
      Sample deliverable prepared as an illustrative example. Findings and the
      client are fictional. Methodology and format reflect a real Design System
      Health Audit engagement.
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>

<style>
  /* Cover variant of the hero: tighter, with a metadata strip. */
  .cover .sub {
    font-size: 15px;
  }
  .cover .meta {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 22px;
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--on-dark);
    border-top: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.25);
    padding-top: 14px;
  }
  .cover .meta b {
    color: #fff;
    display: block;
    font-size: 11px;
    letter-spacing: 0.5px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 2px;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Scorecard */
  .scores {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
    gap: 12px;
    margin: 6px 0;
  }
  .score {
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 14px;
    text-align: center;
    background: #fbf9f6;
  }
  .score .n {
    font-size: 26px;
    font-weight: 800;
    color: var(--accent);
  }
  .score .l {
    font-size: 11.5px;
    color: var(--muted);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.6px;
    margin-top: 2px;
  }
  .grade {
    display: inline-block;
    min-width: 30px;
  }
  .note {
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .score-note {
    margin-top: 12px;
  }
  .legend-heading {
    margin-top: 18px;
  }
  .findings-heading {
    margin-top: 8px;
  }

  /* Severity legend row */
  .legend {
    display: flex;
    gap: 16px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    font-size: 12.5px;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin: 4px 0 2px;
  }

  /* Findings: card with a severity-colored left border. The border is a
     redundant cue; severity is already carried by the .sev badge's shape and
     text, so removing color still leaves the severity legible. */
  .finding {
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-left-width: 4px;
    border-radius: 10px;
    padding: 16px 18px;
    margin: 12px 0;
    background: var(--card);
  }
  .finding.crit {
    border-left-color: var(--crit-accent);
  }
  .finding.med {
    border-left-color: var(--warn-accent);
  }
  .finding.low {
    border-left-color: var(--low-accent);
  }
  .finding .head {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: space-between;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: 12px;
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }
  .finding .id {
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--muted);
    font-weight: 600;
  }
  .finding h3 {
    margin: 2px 0 4px;
  }
  .finding .where {
    font-size: 12.5px;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }
  .finding .label {
    font-size: 11px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.6px;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-weight: 700;
    margin: 10px 0 2px;
  }
  .finding code {
    font-size: 12.5px;
    background: var(--chip);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }
  pre.code {
    background: #241f1d;
    color: #f1ece4;
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 12px 14px;
    overflow: auto;
    font-size: 12.5px;
    line-height: 1.5;
    margin: 6px 0 4px;
  }
  pre.code .c {
    color: var(--on-dark-dim);
  }
  .impact {
    background: var(--low-bg);
    border: 1px solid var(--low-bd);
    border-radius: 8px;
    padding: 9px 12px;
    font-size: 13px;
    color: var(--low-ink);
    margin-top: 8px;
  }

  /* Roadmap table */
  table {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    font-size: 13.5px;
    margin: 6px 0;
  }
  th,
  td {
    text-align: left;
    padding: 9px 10px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--line);
    vertical-align: top;
  }
  th {
    font-size: 11px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.6px;
    color: var(--accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }
  td .eff {
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--ink);
  }

  .report-foot {
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--muted);
    border-top: 1px solid var(--line);
    margin-top: 26px;
    padding-top: 14px;
  }

  @media (max-width: 680px) {
    .scores {
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr);
    }
  }

  /* Print: the sample should read as a real deliverable on paper. Keep the
     cover gradient (exact color), drop card shadows. */
  @media print {
    body {
      background: #fff;
    }
    section.card,
    .finding {
      box-shadow: none;
    }
    .cover {
      -webkit-print-color-adjust: exact;
      print-color-adjust: exact;
    }
  }
</style>
